# CLAUDE.md — Genomics & Molecular Biology Lab

## Project overview

This lab studies gene regulation in neurodevelopment using single-cell and bulk RNA-seq, ATAC-seq, and CUT&Tag. We work primarily with mouse models and human iPSC-derived organoids.

## Preferred tools

- Language: Python 3.11+ (primary), R 4.3+ (for specific Bioconductor packages only)
- Python packages: scanpy 1.10+, pandas 2.x, numpy, seaborn 0.13+, matplotlib, pydeseq2, scikit-learn, anndata
- R packages (when needed): DESeq2, clusterProfiler, GenomicRanges
- Environment manager: conda/mamba with environment.yml files
- Version control: git, with meaningful commit messages

## Data conventions

- Raw data: `data/raw/` — NEVER modify files here
- Processed data: `data/processed/`
- Reference files: `data/references/`
- Genome build: GRCh38 (human) or GRCm39 (mouse)
- Gene annotation: Ensembl release 110
- File naming: `{date}_{descriptor}_{version}.{ext}` (e.g., `2025-03-01_counts_filtered_v2.csv`)
- AnnData objects: save as `.h5ad` format

## Analysis conventions

- Differential expression: pydeseq2 for bulk RNA-seq, Wilcoxon rank-sum (scanpy) for single-cell
- Always report: log2 fold change, p-value, adjusted p-value, and mean expression
- Multiple testing: Benjamini-Hochberg (FDR < 0.05)
- Minimum 3 biological replicates per condition for any statistical comparison
- For clustering: Leiden algorithm (not Louvain), test multiple resolutions
- Dimensionality reduction: PCA first (50 components), then UMAP for visualization
- Flag for human review: any result with n < 3, any p-value between 0.01 and 0.05, unexpected cell type markers

## Output conventions

- Figures: 300 DPI, PDF for publication, PNG for quick inspection
- Default figure size: 8 × 6 inches (single panel), 12 × 8 (multi-panel)
- Color palette: seaborn "colorblind" palette by default; sequential colormaps use "viridis"
- Never use: rainbow, jet, or red-green colormaps
- Font size: 12pt for axis labels, 14pt for titles
- Always include: axis labels with units, descriptive title, legend when >1 group
- Save figures to `results/figures/` with descriptive names

## Reproducibility

- Always set `random_state=42` for any stochastic method
- Log package versions at the start of analysis scripts
- Save intermediate results to disk so analyses can be resumed
- Use relative paths, never absolute paths

## Code style

- snake_case for variables and functions
- Docstring at the top of every script: purpose, inputs, outputs
- No magic numbers — use named constants or comments
- Prefer explicit over clever — readability matters more than conciseness
